comments.body:
@mklement0 

> Even with respect to parse errors alone I would want a script that calls a non-parseable script to fail right away, even while developing a script.

Command resolution is done at run time (commands are late-bound). A called script won't be compiled until it is called. It may not even be called at all depending on the runtime logic of the calling script.

@BrucePay  I'll address the conceptual issues later; but re your small note:

> you probably don't want syntax errors to be runspace terminating otherwise your interactive session would end the first time you mistyped a command.

Runspace-terminating errors don't terminate interactive sessions; I don't know how interactive sessions are implemented, but executing something like `Throw "a fit"` on the command line does _not_ terminate the session.

>  I've called it a script-terminating error and then, sensing it might not be the best term,

Script-terminating is generally fine. Or "terminates the current thread of execution".

> Therefore, what I was really advocating was to treat cases such as 1 / 0 and [int]::Parse('foo') the same as Throw "a fit", i.e., to treat them as fatal errors (by default).

That's easy - put a trap at the top level of your script:
```
trap { break }
& {
    &{
        foreach ($i in 0..5)
        {
            1/$i
            "Hello"
        }
    }
}
```
This will turn statement-terminating error into a "fatal" one.
